QBE is useful partly because its input language is small enough for a new compiler author to inspect directly. A tiny function has this shape:

```text
export function w $max(w %a, w %b) {
@start
  %cmp =w csgtw %a, %b
  jnz %cmp, @left, @right
@left
  ret %a
@right
  ret %b
}
```

The frontend has already chosen concrete machine-sized types (`w`, `l`, `s`, `d`) and explicit control flow. QBE then handles SSA cleanup, instruction selection, register allocation, and ABI details. The generic lesson is to separate "make semantics explicit" from "perform heroic optimization": a small backend can be enough if the language values bootstrapability and implementation transparency.
